INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which Helm command renders a chart locally to YAML (without installing it) so you can inspect or commit the manifests?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"helm install --dry-run --debug"},{"id":"b","text":"helm template <release> <chart>"},{"id":"c","text":"helm render <release> <chart>"},{"id":"d","text":"helm get manifest <release>"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`helm template` renders the chart to stdout without contacting a cluster. `helm install --dry-run` simulates an install but still requires a kubeconfig and release name; `helm get manifest` reads back an installed release.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://helm.sh/docs/topics/charts/","label":"Helm Docs — Charts"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which Helm command renders a chart locally to YAML (without installing it) so you can inspect or commit the manifests?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$To install argo-cd 7.7.3 with the CRDs already managed separately, which value should be passed?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"--set crds.install=false"},{"id":"b","text":"--skip-crds"},{"id":"c","text":"--no-hooks"},{"id":"d","text":"--set createNamespace=false"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The argo-cd chart exposes `crds.install` to decouple CRD lifecycle from the release. `--skip-crds` is a Helm-level flag that does not exist on `template`/`install` for arbitrary charts in the same way; the chart-specific value is the documented path.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://helm.sh/docs/topics/charts/","label":"Helm Docs — Charts"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$To install argo-cd 7.7.3 with the CRDs already managed separately, which value should be passed?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You need to extract every CustomResourceDefinition installed by cert-manager into a single YAML file. Which command works?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl get crd cert-manager -o yaml > resources.yaml"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl get crd | grep cert-manager | awk '{print $1}' | xargs -I{} kubectl get crd {} -o yaml >> resources.yaml"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl explain crd --recursive > resources.yaml"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl describe crd > resources.yaml"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The filter-and-xargs pipeline lists every CRD whose name contains `cert-manager` and exports each as YAML. `kubectl describe` is human-formatted, not re-applicable; `kubectl explain` documents schema, not instances.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/extend-kubernetes/api-extension/custom-resources/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Custom Resources"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You need to extract every CustomResourceDefinition installed by cert-manager into a single YAML file. Which command works?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You are migrating worker nodes from containerd to cri-dockerd (Mirantis). After installing the `cri-dockerd` package, which command persists the kernel-module/sysctl prerequisites across reboots?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"echo 'net.ipv4.ip_forward=1' > /etc/sysctl.conf"},{"id":"b","text":"Create /etc/sysctl.d/cka.conf with the needed entries and run `sudo sysctl --system`"},{"id":"c","text":"kubeadm config images pull"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl edit kubelet to add `--ip-forward=1`"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Drop-in files under `/etc/sysctl.d/` are reloaded by `sysctl --system`, persisting `net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables`, `net.ipv4.ip_forward`, etc. Editing `/etc/sysctl.conf` works but is discouraged; the others are unrelated.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/container-runtimes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Container Runtimes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You are migrating worker nodes from containerd to cri-dockerd (Mirantis). After installing the `cri-dockerd` package, which command persists the kernel-module/sysctl prerequisites across reboots?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Select ALL true statements about the Kubernetes control plane.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kube-apiserver is the only component that talks directly to etcd in a default kubeadm install."},{"id":"b","text":"kube-scheduler watches for unscheduled Pods and assigns them to nodes via the apiserver."},{"id":"c","text":"kube-controller-manager runs as a Deployment in kube-system."},{"id":"d","text":"etcd is the cluster's single source of truth for object state."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","b","d"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$On kubeadm clusters, control-plane components run as **static Pods** managed by the kubelet from `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/`, NOT as Deployments. The other three statements are correct.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/configure-upgrade-etcd/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Operating etcd"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Select ALL true statements about the Kubernetes control plane.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Deployment must have a sidecar that tails a log file the main container writes. Which volume type lets both containers share the file inside the Pod?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"hostPath"},{"id":"b","text":"emptyDir"},{"id":"c","text":"configMap"},{"id":"d","text":"persistentVolumeClaim (RWO)"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`emptyDir` is created when the Pod is bound to a node and is shared by every container in the Pod — the standard pattern for sidecar log tailing. hostPath ties to the node filesystem; PVC RWO is unnecessary overhead for ephemeral logs.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Deployment must have a sidecar that tails a log file the main container writes. Which volume type lets both containers share the file inside the Pod?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You taint `node01` with `IT=Kiddie:NoSchedule`. Which toleration on a Pod is necessary and sufficient for it to schedule there?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"`{ key: \"IT\", operator: \"Exists\", effect: \"NoExecute\" }`"},{"id":"b","text":"`{ key: \"IT\", operator: \"Equal\", value: \"Kiddie\", effect: \"NoSchedule\" }`"},{"id":"c","text":"`{ key: \"Kiddie\", operator: \"Equal\", value: \"IT\", effect: \"NoSchedule\" }`"},{"id":"d","text":"No toleration is needed; taints affect only existing Pods."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A toleration must match the taint exactly on key/value/effect (or use the Exists operator with matching key + effect). NoSchedule blocks new scheduling; NoExecute additionally evicts running Pods.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/scheduling-eviction/taint-and-toleration/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Taints and Tolerations"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You taint `node01` with `IT=Kiddie:NoSchedule`. Which toleration on a Pod is necessary and sufficient for it to schedule there?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You create a PriorityClass `high-priority` with value 9_999_999 and patch Deployment `busybox-logger` to use it. The Pods are not preempting lower-priority Pods. What is the MOST likely cause?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"You need to set `preemptionPolicy: Never`."},{"id":"b","text":"The Deployment's existing ReplicaSet still references the old template — restart the rollout (e.g. `kubectl rollout restart deploy busybox-logger`)."},{"id":"c","text":"PriorityClasses below 1_000_000_000 are ignored."},{"id":"d","text":"PriorityClass only affects DaemonSets."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Patching the Deployment spec updates the template but the running Pods belong to the previous ReplicaSet; a `rollout restart` (or any change that creates a new RS) is needed to roll the Pods over with the new priority. Priority is honored on scheduling/preemption.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/scheduling-eviction/pod-priority-preemption/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Pod Priority and Preemption"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You create a PriorityClass `high-priority` with value 9_999_999 and patch Deployment `busybox-logger` to use it. The Pods are not preempting lower-priority Pods. What is the MOST likely cause?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command exposes Deployment `frontend` on a port reachable on every node's IP at a high (30000–32767) port?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl expose deploy frontend --type=ClusterIP --port=80"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl expose deploy frontend --type=NodePort --port=80"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl expose deploy frontend --type=ExternalName --port=80"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl expose deploy frontend --type=Headless --port=80"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$NodePort allocates a port from `--service-node-port-range` (default 30000–32767) on every node. ClusterIP is internal-only; ExternalName is a CNAME alias; "Headless" is `clusterIP: None`, not a type.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Services"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command exposes Deployment `frontend` on a port reachable on every node's IP at a high (30000–32767) port?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$An Ingress for the nginx-ingress controller routes `/echo` on host `example.org` to Service `echoserver-service:8080`. From outside the cluster on a NodePort install, the correct test command is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"curl http://example.org:80/echo"},{"id":"b","text":"curl -H \"Host: example.org\" http://<node-ip>:<ingress-nodeport>/echo"},{"id":"c","text":"curl http://<service-cluster-ip>:8080/echo"},{"id":"d","text":"curl --resolve example.org:80:127.0.0.1 http://example.org/echo"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Without DNS, you must hit the ingress-nginx controller's NodePort on any node IP and pass `Host: example.org` so the Ingress host rule matches. Hitting the backend Service cluster IP bypasses the Ingress and ignores the path rule.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/ingress/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Ingress"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$An Ingress for the nginx-ingress controller routes `/echo` on host `example.org` to Service `echoserver-service:8080`. From outside the cluster on a NodePort install, the correct test command is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You want to terminate TLS at the cluster edge using the Gateway API and the nginx-gateway-fabric controller. Which Gateway listener config is correct?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"protocol: HTTPS, port: 443, tls.mode: Passthrough, certificateRefs omitted"},{"id":"b","text":"protocol: HTTPS, port: 443, tls.mode: Terminate, certificateRefs: [{ kind: Secret, name: web-tls }]"},{"id":"c","text":"protocol: TLS, port: 443, tls.mode: Terminate, certificateRefs omitted"},{"id":"d","text":"protocol: HTTP, port: 443, tls.mode: Terminate"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$TLS termination requires `tls.mode: Terminate` plus a Secret of type `kubernetes.io/tls` via `certificateRefs`. Passthrough forwards the TLS connection unmodified. Listener protocol must be HTTPS for HTTPRoute attachment.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://gateway-api.sigs.k8s.io/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Gateway API"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You want to terminate TLS at the cluster edge using the Gateway API and the nginx-gateway-fabric controller. Which Gateway listener config is correct?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 4, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A NetworkPolicy in namespace `backend` selects pods labelled `app=backend` and allows ingress from pods labelled `app=frontend` in namespace `frontend`. Select ALL true statements.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The `from` list must combine a namespaceSelector and a podSelector inside a single peer object (AND), not as separate items (OR)."},{"id":"b","text":"Two separate peer items {namespaceSelector}, {podSelector} mean \"any pod from that namespace OR any pod in this namespace with that label\"."},{"id":"c","text":"A CNI implementing NetworkPolicy (e.g. Calico, Cilium) must be installed."},{"id":"d","text":"The policy implicitly allows all egress from the backend pods."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","b","c","d"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$All four are true. Combining selectors inside one `from` peer object is AND; separate items are OR. Egress is only restricted if the policy lists `policyTypes: [Egress]`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/network-policies/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Network Policies"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A NetworkPolicy in namespace `backend` selects pods labelled `app=backend` and allows ingress from pods labelled `app=frontend` in namespace `frontend`. Select ALL true statements.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which annotation marks a StorageClass as the cluster default?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"storageclass.kubernetes.io/is-default-class: \"true\""},{"id":"b","text":"storage.k8s.io/default: \"yes\""},{"id":"c","text":"kubernetes.io/default-sc: \"true\""},{"id":"d","text":"volume.beta.kubernetes.io/default: \"true\""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The default StorageClass is identified by the annotation `storageclass.kubernetes.io/is-default-class: "true"`. At most one default should be set at a time; PVCs without `storageClassName` use it.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/storage-classes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Storage Classes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which annotation marks a StorageClass as the cluster default?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A PersistentVolume is `Released` with reclaimPolicy `Retain` and a stale `claimRef`. A new PVC matches it on size and storageClassName but binding fails. What MUST you do to allow rebind?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Delete the PV."},{"id":"b","text":"Edit the PV and remove the `spec.claimRef` block."},{"id":"c","text":"Change reclaim policy to `Delete`."},{"id":"d","text":"Scale the workload to zero and back."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A Retained PV keeps its `claimRef` even after the original PVC is gone, blocking new bindings. Remove `claimRef` (and any obsolete `pv.kubernetes.io/bind-completed` annotation) so the PV returns to `Available`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Persistent Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A PersistentVolume is `Released` with reclaimPolicy `Retain` and a stale `claimRef`. A new PVC matches it on size and storageClassName but binding fails. What MUST you do to allow rebind?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$On a kubeadm control-plane node, the apiserver static Pod manifest lives at:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/kubernetes/static/kube-apiserver.yaml"},{"id":"c","text":"/var/lib/kubelet/config/kube-apiserver.yaml"},{"id":"d","text":"/etc/systemd/system/kube-apiserver.service"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$kubeadm places control-plane static Pod manifests in `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/`. The kubelet watches this directory and (re)starts the corresponding Pods as files change.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$On a kubeadm control-plane node, the apiserver static Pod manifest lives at:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$The apiserver is down because `--etcd-servers=https://127.0.0.1:2380` was set in the static Pod manifest. Which is the correct fix?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Set `--etcd-servers=https://127.0.0.1:2379` (etcd client port) in /etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml"},{"id":"b","text":"Restart docker"},{"id":"c","text":"Run `kubeadm reset`"},{"id":"d","text":"Add `--insecure-port=8080` to the manifest"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$etcd serves clients on **2379** and peer traffic on **2380**. The apiserver must connect to the client port. After saving the manifest the kubelet recreates the static Pod automatically.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/configure-upgrade-etcd/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Operating etcd"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$The apiserver is down because `--etcd-servers=https://127.0.0.1:2380` was set in the static Pod manifest. Which is the correct fix?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A pod is in `Pending` with the event "0/3 nodes are available: 3 node(s) had untolerated taint {node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane: }". The fix that is MOST appropriate for a normal workload is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a toleration for the control-plane taint to the Pod."},{"id":"b","text":"Schedule the Pod on a worker node by removing the nodeSelector or adding a worker label."},{"id":"c","text":"Remove the control-plane taint from all nodes."},{"id":"d","text":"Set `spec.hostNetwork: true`."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The control-plane taint exists to keep general workloads off the control plane. Either add a worker to the cluster or remove the targeting constraint that forces it onto control plane. Removing the taint cluster-wide is bad practice for production.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/scheduling-eviction/taint-and-toleration/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Taints and Tolerations"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A pod is in `Pending` with the event "0/3 nodes are available: 3 node(s) had untolerated taint {node-role.kubernetes.io/control-plane: }". The fix that is MOST appropriate for a normal workload is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$`kubectl logs <pod>` returns "Error from server (BadRequest): previous terminated container ... not found". The container has only ever started once and is currently Running. Which flag explains the error?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"--follow"},{"id":"b","text":"--previous"},{"id":"c","text":"--tail=0"},{"id":"d","text":"--all-containers"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`--previous` asks the kubelet for the prior instance's logs, which only exist after at least one restart. The fix is to drop `--previous` (or wait for a restart).$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/cluster-administration/logging/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Logging Architecture"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$`kubectl logs <pod>` returns "Error from server (BadRequest): previous terminated container ... not found". The container has only ever started once and is currently Running. Which flag explains the error?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A node is `NotReady`. You SSH in and check `systemctl status kubelet` — it is failing to start with "open /var/lib/kubelet/config.yaml: no such file". The MOST likely root cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The container runtime is not installed."},{"id":"b","text":"The node was never bootstrapped via `kubeadm join` (or its config was deleted)."},{"id":"c","text":"kube-proxy is crashing."},{"id":"d","text":"CoreDNS is misconfigured."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubeadm join` writes `/var/lib/kubelet/config.yaml` from the cluster's kubelet-config ConfigMap. If absent, the node has not been joined or its files were removed.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A node is `NotReady`. You SSH in and check `systemctl status kubelet` — it is failing to start with "open /var/lib/kubelet/config.yaml: no such file". The MOST likely root cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A pod has `requests.memory: 200Mi, limits.memory: 256Mi`. It restarts with `OOMKilled` under load. Which is the safest first remediation?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the memory LIMIT after profiling."},{"id":"b","text":"Increase the memory REQUEST only."},{"id":"c","text":"Add `--oom-score-adj=-1000` to the kubelet."},{"id":"d","text":"Disable the liveness probe."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$OOMKilled means the container exceeded its `limits.memory`. Profile actual usage and raise the limit. Increasing only the request changes scheduling but not the cgroup memory cap.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Resource Management"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A pod has `requests.memory: 200Mi, limits.memory: 256Mi`. It restarts with `OOMKilled` under load. Which is the safest first remediation?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Before running `kubeadm init`, swap must be disabled. Which command disables it for the current boot?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"swapoff -a"},{"id":"b","text":"systemctl disable swap"},{"id":"c","text":"kubeadm config swap off"},{"id":"d","text":"sysctl -w vm.swappiness=0"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`swapoff -a` disables all swap immediately. To persist across reboots you also comment the swap entry in `/etc/fstab`. `vm.swappiness=0` only discourages swapping; it does not disable it.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Before running `kubeadm init`, swap must be disabled. Which command disables it for the current boot?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command prints the join command (with token and CA hash) for adding a new worker to an existing kubeadm cluster?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubeadm token create --print-join-command"},{"id":"b","text":"kubeadm join --generate"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl get token -n kube-system"},{"id":"d","text":"kubeadm init phase bootstrap-token"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubeadm token create --print-join-command` mints a fresh bootstrap token and prints the full `kubeadm join` line including `--discovery-token-ca-cert-hash`. Tokens default to a 24h TTL.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command prints the join command (with token and CA hash) for adding a new worker to an existing kubeadm cluster?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You must give ServiceAccount `ci` in namespace `build` permission to create Jobs in that namespace only. The correct binding subject is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kind: User, name: ci"},{"id":"b","text":"kind: ServiceAccount, name: ci, namespace: build"},{"id":"c","text":"kind: Group, name: system:serviceaccounts"},{"id":"d","text":"kind: ServiceAccount, name: system:ci"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A RoleBinding subject for a ServiceAccount uses `kind: ServiceAccount` with the `name` and `namespace`. Binding to the broad `system:serviceaccounts` group would over-grant to every SA.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/rbac/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — RBAC"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You must give ServiceAccount `ci` in namespace `build` permission to create Jobs in that namespace only. The correct binding subject is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$After editing `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml`, how does the change take effect?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Run `systemctl restart kube-apiserver`."},{"id":"b","text":"The kubelet detects the file change and recreates the static Pod automatically."},{"id":"c","text":"Run `kubectl rollout restart -n kube-system deploy/kube-apiserver`."},{"id":"d","text":"Run `kubeadm upgrade apply`."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The kubelet watches `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/` and restarts the corresponding static Pod whenever the manifest changes. There is no systemd unit or Deployment for control-plane components on kubeadm clusters.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$After editing `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-apiserver.yaml`, how does the change take effect?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which etcdctl invocation correctly takes a snapshot when etcd uses client TLS certificates?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot save /backup/snap.db --endpoints=https://127.0.0.1:2379 --cacert=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/ca.crt --cert=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.crt --key=/etc/kubernetes/pki/etcd/server.key"},{"id":"b","text":"etcdctl backup --data-dir /var/lib/etcd"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl exec etcd -- snapshot save"},{"id":"d","text":"ETCDCTL_API=2 etcdctl snapshot save /backup/snap.db"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$API v3 snapshots require `--endpoints` plus the CA, client cert, and key. The legacy `etcdctl backup` and API v2 do not produce a v3 snapshot usable by `snapshot restore`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/configure-upgrade-etcd/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Operating etcd"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which etcdctl invocation correctly takes a snapshot when etcd uses client TLS certificates?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You need to cordon `node01` so the scheduler stops placing NEW Pods there but existing Pods keep running. The command is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl drain node01"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl cordon node01"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl taint node node01 key=val:NoExecute"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl delete node node01"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl cordon` marks the node `SchedulingDisabled` without evicting Pods. `drain` additionally evicts Pods; a NoExecute taint would evict non-tolerating Pods.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubectl Reference"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You need to cordon `node01` so the scheduler stops placing NEW Pods there but existing Pods keep running. The command is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You must restore an etcd snapshot to recover a cluster. Before pointing the etcd static Pod at the restored data directory, you should:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Leave the apiserver running so it can replay the WAL."},{"id":"b","text":"Stop the kube-apiserver (move its manifest out of /etc/kubernetes/manifests) so it does not write during the restore."},{"id":"c","text":"Delete /var/lib/kubelet."},{"id":"d","text":"Run `kubeadm reset` first."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$During an etcd restore the apiserver must not be writing to etcd. Moving the apiserver (and etcd) static-Pod manifests out, performing the restore, then restoring the manifests is the safe sequence.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/configure-upgrade-etcd/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Operating etcd"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You must restore an etcd snapshot to recover a cluster. Before pointing the etcd static Pod at the restored data directory, you should:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$On the first control-plane node you run `kubeadm upgrade apply v1.32.1`. To upgrade an additional control-plane node you then run:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubeadm upgrade apply v1.32.1 again"},{"id":"b","text":"kubeadm upgrade node"},{"id":"c","text":"kubeadm init --upgrade"},{"id":"d","text":"kubeadm join --upgrade"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Only the first control-plane node runs `kubeadm upgrade apply`. Every other control-plane and worker node runs `kubeadm upgrade node`, then upgrades the kubelet/kubectl packages.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/kubeadm/kubeadm-upgrade/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Upgrading kubeadm clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$On the first control-plane node you run `kubeadm upgrade apply v1.32.1`. To upgrade an additional control-plane node you then run:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command shows whether control-plane component certificates managed by kubeadm are close to expiring?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubeadm certs check-expiration"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl get certificates -A"},{"id":"c","text":"openssl verify /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"kubeadm config view"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubeadm certs check-expiration` lists every kubeadm-managed certificate and its expiry. `kubeadm certs renew` renews them. `kubectl get certificates` lists cert-manager CRs, not control-plane PKI.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command shows whether control-plane component certificates managed by kubeadm are close to expiring?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Select ALL true statements about kubeconfig files.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"A context binds a cluster, a user, and an optional namespace."},{"id":"b","text":"`kubectl config use-context <name>` switches the active context."},{"id":"c","text":"Client certificate data can be embedded base64 or referenced by file path."},{"id":"d","text":"The KUBECONFIG env var can merge multiple kubeconfig files."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","b","c","d"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$All four are correct. A context ties cluster+user(+namespace); `use-context` switches; credentials may be inline (`*-data`) or file paths; `KUBECONFIG=a:b:c` merges files at load time.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubectl Reference"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Select ALL true statements about kubeconfig files.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$TRUE_FALSE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$On a default kubeadm cluster, kube-scheduler and kube-controller-manager run as Deployments in the kube-system namespace.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"},{"id":"c","text":""},{"id":"d","text":""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$False. They run as static Pods managed by the kubelet from `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/`, not as Deployments. Only add-ons like CoreDNS run as Deployments.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$On a default kubeadm cluster, kube-scheduler and kube-controller-manager run as Deployments in the kube-system namespace.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command scales Deployment `web` to 5 replicas imperatively?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl scale deploy web --replicas=5"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl edit deploy web --replicas=5"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl set replicas deploy/web 5"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl patch deploy web --replicas 5"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl scale deploy web --replicas=5` directly updates the replica count. `kubectl set` has no `replicas` subcommand and `patch` needs a JSON/strategic merge body.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Deployments"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command scales Deployment `web` to 5 replicas imperatively?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Pod must only schedule on nodes labelled `disktype=ssd`. The simplest spec field is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"spec.nodeName: ssd"},{"id":"b","text":"spec.nodeSelector: { disktype: ssd }"},{"id":"c","text":"spec.tolerations"},{"id":"d","text":"spec.priorityClassName: ssd"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`nodeSelector` is the simplest hard node-constraint, matching node labels exactly. `nodeName` pins to one specific node by name; tolerations relate to taints, not labels.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/scheduling-eviction/assign-pod-node/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Assigning Pods to Nodes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Pod must only schedule on nodes labelled `disktype=ssd`. The simplest spec field is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A CronJob should run every 5 minutes. The correct `schedule` value is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"\"*/5 * * * *\""},{"id":"b","text":"\"5 * * * *\""},{"id":"c","text":"\"@every5m\""},{"id":"d","text":"\"0/5 0 0 0 0\""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$CronJob uses standard cron syntax: `*/5 * * * *` means "every 5th minute". `5 * * * *` runs once per hour at minute 5.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Deployments"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A CronJob should run every 5 minutes. The correct `schedule` value is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You want to roll back Deployment `api` to its previous revision after a bad image. The command is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl rollout undo deploy/api"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl rollout pause deploy/api"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl delete deploy api && kubectl apply -f api.yaml"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl set image deploy/api api=previous"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl rollout undo deploy/api` reverts to the prior ReplicaSet revision. Add `--to-revision=N` for a specific revision (see `kubectl rollout history`).$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Deployments"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You want to roll back Deployment `api` to its previous revision after a bad image. The command is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Select ALL true statements about static Pods.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"They are defined by manifest files in the kubelet `staticPodPath` (default /etc/kubernetes/manifests)."},{"id":"b","text":"The apiserver creates a read-only mirror Pod so they appear in `kubectl get pods`."},{"id":"c","text":"You can delete a static Pod with `kubectl delete pod` permanently."},{"id":"d","text":"They are managed directly by the kubelet, not by a controller."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","b","d"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Deleting the mirror Pod via kubectl does NOT remove a static Pod — the kubelet recreates it; you must remove the manifest file. The other statements are correct.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Select ALL true statements about static Pods.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Deployment uses `strategy.type: Recreate`. During an image update, the rollout behavior is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"New Pods come up before old Pods are terminated."},{"id":"b","text":"All old Pods are terminated first, then new Pods are created (brief downtime)."},{"id":"c","text":"One Pod at a time is replaced."},{"id":"d","text":"The update is rejected — Recreate is invalid for Deployments."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The `Recreate` strategy kills all existing Pods before creating new ones, causing a short outage. `RollingUpdate` is the default that avoids downtime via surge/unavailable controls.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Deployments"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Deployment uses `strategy.type: Recreate`. During an image update, the rollout behavior is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 2, $k8s$TRUE_FALSE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Job with `completions: 5` and `parallelism: 2` runs at most 2 Pods at a time until 5 succeed.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"},{"id":"c","text":""},{"id":"d","text":""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$True. `parallelism` caps concurrent Pods; `completions` is the total number of successful Pod runs required before the Job is complete.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/deployment/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Deployments"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Job with `completions: 5` and `parallelism: 2` runs at most 2 Pods at a time until 5 succeed.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Service of type ClusterIP is reachable:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"only from within the cluster"},{"id":"b","text":"from any external client on the node IP"},{"id":"c","text":"only from the control-plane nodes"},{"id":"d","text":"from the internet via the cloud load balancer"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$ClusterIP is the default type and is reachable only from inside the cluster (Pods/Nodes). External exposure requires NodePort, LoadBalancer, or an Ingress/Gateway.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Services"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Service of type ClusterIP is reachable:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$CoreDNS runs in kube-system. To verify in-cluster DNS, you exec a debug Pod and run:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"nslookup kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local"},{"id":"b","text":"ping coredns"},{"id":"c","text":"curl http://kube-dns:53"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl dns test"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Resolving `kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local` from a Pod confirms CoreDNS and the kube-dns Service work. ICMP/HTTP against DNS does not validate name resolution.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/dns-pod-service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — DNS for Services and Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$CoreDNS runs in kube-system. To verify in-cluster DNS, you exec a debug Pod and run:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A ClusterIP Service has a selector `app=web` but no endpoints appear. The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"No running Pods carry the label `app=web` (or they are not Ready)."},{"id":"b","text":"kube-proxy is not installed."},{"id":"c","text":"The Service needs a NodePort."},{"id":"d","text":"CoreDNS is down."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Endpoints (EndpointSlices) are populated from Ready Pods matching the selector. A label mismatch or unready Pods yields an empty endpoint list and connection failures.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Services"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A ClusterIP Service has a selector `app=web` but no endpoints appear. The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$An Ingress resource exists but returns nothing. `kubectl get ingress` shows an empty ADDRESS column. The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"No Ingress controller is installed/running to satisfy the Ingress."},{"id":"b","text":"The Service is ClusterIP."},{"id":"c","text":"TLS is not configured."},{"id":"d","text":"The path type is Prefix."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$An Ingress object is inert without a controller (ingress-nginx, etc.) watching and programming it. No controller means no ADDRESS and no routing.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/ingress/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Ingress"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$An Ingress resource exists but returns nothing. `kubectl get ingress` shows an empty ADDRESS column. The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You need an Ingress path that matches `/app` and any sub-path like `/app/x`. The pathType should be:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Exact"},{"id":"b","text":"Prefix"},{"id":"c","text":"ImplementationSpecific only"},{"id":"d","text":"Regex"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`Prefix` matches the path element prefix, so `/app` also matches `/app/x`. `Exact` requires an exact string match; `Regex` is not a valid pathType value.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/ingress/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Ingress"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You need an Ingress path that matches `/app` and any sub-path like `/app/x`. The pathType should be:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A NetworkPolicy should allow ingress to `app=db` Pods ONLY on TCP 5432. The rule includes:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"ports: [{ protocol: TCP, port: 5432 }] under an ingress rule"},{"id":"b","text":"egress: [{ ports: [{ port: 5432 }] }]"},{"id":"c","text":"policyTypes: [Egress] only"},{"id":"d","text":"a Service annotation `allow-port: 5432`"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Port restrictions are declared in the `ports` list of an ingress (or egress) rule. Combined with a `from` peer this allows only matching sources on TCP 5432.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/network-policies/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Network Policies"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A NetworkPolicy should allow ingress to `app=db` Pods ONLY on TCP 5432. The rule includes:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which Service type creates a DNS CNAME to an external hostname with no proxying?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"ClusterIP"},{"id":"b","text":"NodePort"},{"id":"c","text":"ExternalName"},{"id":"d","text":"LoadBalancer"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["c"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`ExternalName` returns a CNAME record to the configured `externalName` hostname; kube-proxy does not proxy traffic and no cluster IP is allocated.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Services"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which Service type creates a DNS CNAME to an external hostname with no proxying?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Select ALL true statements about kube-proxy.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"It programs iptables (or IPVS) rules to implement Service virtual IPs."},{"id":"b","text":"It typically runs as a DaemonSet on every node."},{"id":"c","text":"It resolves Service DNS names."},{"id":"d","text":"In IPVS mode it provides additional load-balancing algorithms."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","b","d"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$DNS resolution is CoreDNS, not kube-proxy. kube-proxy implements Service VIP routing via iptables/IPVS and runs as a per-node DaemonSet; IPVS adds algorithms like rr/lc.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Services"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Select ALL true statements about kube-proxy.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 2, $k8s$TRUE_FALSE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A headless Service is created by setting `spec.clusterIP: None`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"},{"id":"c","text":""},{"id":"d","text":""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$True. With `clusterIP: None` and a selector, DNS returns the individual Pod A records instead of a single virtual IP — the basis for StatefulSet stable Pod DNS.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/dns-pod-service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — DNS for Services and Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A headless Service is created by setting `spec.clusterIP: None`.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A PVC stays `Pending` and `kubectl describe pvc` shows "no persistent volumes available for this claim and no storage class is set". The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"No matching PV exists and no (default) StorageClass can dynamically provision one."},{"id":"b","text":"The Pod is not scheduled."},{"id":"c","text":"reclaimPolicy is Retain."},{"id":"d","text":"The PVC requested ReadWriteMany."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Without a matching pre-provisioned PV and with no StorageClass (or default) for dynamic provisioning, the PVC cannot bind and stays Pending.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Persistent Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A PVC stays `Pending` and `kubectl describe pvc` shows "no persistent volumes available for this claim and no storage class is set". The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A PV has `persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Delete`. When its bound PVC is deleted:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The PV becomes Available for reuse."},{"id":"b","text":"The PV and the underlying storage asset are deleted."},{"id":"c","text":"The PV becomes Released and is retained."},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing happens until the node reboots."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$With `Delete`, removing the PVC also deletes the PV object and the backing volume (for dynamically provisioned volumes). `Retain` keeps both for manual reclamation.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Persistent Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A PV has `persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Delete`. When its bound PVC is deleted:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Multiple Pods across different nodes must write to the same volume simultaneously. The PVC accessMode must be:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"ReadWriteOnce"},{"id":"b","text":"ReadWriteMany"},{"id":"c","text":"ReadOnlyMany"},{"id":"d","text":"ReadWriteOncePod"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$ReadWriteMany allows multiple nodes to mount the volume read-write (e.g. NFS/CephFS). ReadWriteOnce is single-node; ReadWriteOncePod restricts to a single Pod.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Persistent Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Multiple Pods across different nodes must write to the same volume simultaneously. The PVC accessMode must be:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$To mount a ConfigMap key `app.conf` as a file at `/etc/app/app.conf`, you use:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"a configMap volume with an items[] mapping plus a volumeMount"},{"id":"b","text":"an emptyDir volume"},{"id":"c","text":"env.valueFrom.configMapKeyRef"},{"id":"d","text":"a hostPath volume"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A `configMap` volume (optionally with `items` to map specific keys to paths) mounted via `volumeMounts` projects the data as files. `configMapKeyRef` injects it as an env var, not a file.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$To mount a ConfigMap key `app.conf` as a file at `/etc/app/app.conf`, you use:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 2, $k8s$TRUE_FALSE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A PVC with accessMode ReadWriteOnce can be mounted read-write by Pods on only one node at a time.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"},{"id":"c","text":""},{"id":"d","text":""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$True. ReadWriteOnce permits read-write mounting by one node; multiple Pods on that same node may share it. Cross-node concurrent write needs ReadWriteMany.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Persistent Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A PVC with accessMode ReadWriteOnce can be mounted read-write by Pods on only one node at a time.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command shows recent cluster events sorted by time to triage a failing Pod?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl get events --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl logs events"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl top events"},{"id":"d","text":"journalctl -u events"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl get events --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp` lists events chronologically. `kubectl describe pod` shows events scoped to one object.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command shows recent cluster events sorted by time to triage a failing Pod?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Pod is `CrashLoopBackOff`. The single most useful command to see why the container exits is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl logs <pod> --previous"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl get pod <pod> -o wide"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl top pod <pod>"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl edit pod <pod>"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$CrashLoopBackOff means the container repeatedly exits; `kubectl logs --previous` shows the last terminated container's output (the actual error), since the current instance may not be running.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/cluster-administration/logging/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Logging Architecture"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Pod is `CrashLoopBackOff`. The single most useful command to see why the container exits is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A node shows `MemoryPressure=True` and Pods are being evicted. The first investigative command on the node is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl describe node <node> (review conditions and allocatable)"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl delete node <node>"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl restart docker"},{"id":"d","text":"kubeadm reset"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl describe node` reveals the conditions, allocatable resources, and eviction events so you can identify memory exhaustion before taking action.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A node shows `MemoryPressure=True` and Pods are being evicted. The first investigative command on the node is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Pod is stuck `Terminating` for a long time after deletion. A common safe cause to check first is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"A finalizer on the Pod (or the node is unreachable so the kubelet cannot confirm deletion)."},{"id":"b","text":"The apiserver is down."},{"id":"c","text":"etcd is corrupted."},{"id":"d","text":"kube-proxy crashed."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Pods stuck Terminating are usually waiting on a finalizer or a NotReady/unreachable node where the kubelet cannot confirm container shutdown. `--force --grace-period=0` is the last-resort removal.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubectl Reference"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Pod is stuck `Terminating` for a long time after deletion. A common safe cause to check first is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You need to run an interactive shell in a running Pod's container to debug. The command is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl exec -it <pod> -- /bin/sh"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl attach <pod>"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl run <pod> -- sh"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl debug <pod> --shell"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl exec -it <pod> -- /bin/sh` opens an interactive TTY in the container. `attach` connects to the existing process stdio; `kubectl debug` creates an ephemeral debug container (different use).$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubectl Reference"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You need to run an interactive shell in a running Pod's container to debug. The command is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Pod stays `Pending` and describe shows "Insufficient cpu". The remediation is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Lower the Pod CPU requests or add a node with more allocatable CPU."},{"id":"b","text":"Increase the Pod CPU limit."},{"id":"c","text":"Restart kube-scheduler."},{"id":"d","text":"Add a toleration."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$"Insufficient cpu" means no node has enough allocatable CPU to satisfy the Pod's requests. Reduce requests or add capacity. Limits do not affect scheduling feasibility.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Resource Management"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Pod stays `Pending` and describe shows "Insufficient cpu". The remediation is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$After `kubectl apply`, a container is `RunContainerError` with "exec: \"./start.sh\": permission denied". The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The entrypoint script is not executable / wrong command in the image or spec."},{"id":"b","text":"NetworkPolicy blocks startup."},{"id":"c","text":"The node is NotReady."},{"id":"d","text":"The Service selector is wrong."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$RunContainerError with a permission/exec message points to a bad command, missing executable bit, or wrong path in the image or `command`/`args`. Fix the image or the Pod command.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$After `kubectl apply`, a container is `RunContainerError` with "exec: \"./start.sh\": permission denied". The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$kubelet on a worker is healthy but the node is `NotReady` and `kubectl describe node` shows `NetworkUnavailable=True`. The likely cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The CNI plugin is not installed or its Pods are failing on that node."},{"id":"b","text":"The apiserver cert expired."},{"id":"c","text":"Swap is enabled."},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl is the wrong version."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`NetworkUnavailable=True` indicates the node network (CNI) is not set up. Check the CNI DaemonSet Pods (Calico/Flannel/etc.) on that node and their logs.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/extend-kubernetes/compute-storage-net/network-plugins/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Network Plugins (CNI)"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$kubelet on a worker is healthy but the node is `NotReady` and `kubectl describe node` shows `NetworkUnavailable=True`. The likely cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$The kube-apiserver static Pod keeps restarting. Which log source should you check directly on the control-plane node?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"crictl logs of the apiserver container (or /var/log/pods/...)"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl logs -n kube-system deploy/kube-apiserver"},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl status kube-apiserver"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl get events only"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$When the apiserver is down, kubectl cannot reach it, so inspect the container directly via `crictl ps -a` / `crictl logs` or `/var/log/pods`. There is no apiserver Deployment or systemd unit.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$The kube-apiserver static Pod keeps restarting. Which log source should you check directly on the control-plane node?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A liveness probe is restarting a healthy container repeatedly. The MOST likely misconfiguration is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"initialDelaySeconds is too small / probe path or port is wrong."},{"id":"b","text":"The container has no readiness probe."},{"id":"c","text":"The Service is ClusterIP."},{"id":"d","text":"The image is too large."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A liveness probe firing before the app is ready (low initialDelaySeconds) or pointed at the wrong path/port causes endless restarts. Tune the delay/threshold or fix the probe target.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A liveness probe is restarting a healthy container repeatedly. The MOST likely misconfiguration is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You must collect metrics with `kubectl top nodes` but it returns "Metrics API not available". The fix is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Install/repair the metrics-server in the cluster."},{"id":"b","text":"Restart kube-proxy."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable the dashboard."},{"id":"d","text":"Set --enable-metrics on kubectl."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl top` depends on the metrics-server serving the metrics.k8s.io API. If it is not installed or unhealthy, `top` fails. Deploy/fix metrics-server.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You must collect metrics with `kubectl top nodes` but it returns "Metrics API not available". The fix is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 4, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A worker node is NotReady. Select ALL valid first-step checks.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"`systemctl status kubelet` and `journalctl -u kubelet` on the node."},{"id":"b","text":"`kubectl describe node <node>` for conditions and events."},{"id":"c","text":"Verify the container runtime (`crictl info` / `systemctl status containerd`)."},{"id":"d","text":"Immediately run `kubeadm reset` on the node."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","b","c"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Inspect the kubelet, node conditions, and the runtime first. `kubeadm reset` destroys node state and is never an appropriate first diagnostic step.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"},{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A worker node is NotReady. Select ALL valid first-step checks.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 2, $k8s$TRUE_FALSE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$When the kube-apiserver is unreachable, `kubectl logs` can still retrieve container logs.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"True"},{"id":"b","text":"False"},{"id":"c","text":""},{"id":"d","text":""}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$False. `kubectl logs` proxies through the apiserver to the kubelet. If the apiserver is down you must read logs on the node via `crictl logs` or `/var/log/pods`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/cluster-administration/logging/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Logging Architecture"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P1$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$When the kube-apiserver is unreachable, `kubectl logs` can still retrieve container logs.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$On a kubeadm cluster, what is the recommended order to upgrade the control plane minor version?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubelet → kubeadm → kubectl → apply"},{"id":"b","text":"kubeadm upgrade plan → kubeadm upgrade apply <ver> → upgrade kubelet & kubectl"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl drain → kubeadm reset → kubeadm init"},{"id":"d","text":"helm upgrade kubernetes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Always run `kubeadm upgrade plan` first to confirm the target version, then `kubeadm upgrade apply` on the first control-plane node, then upgrade kubelet/kubectl. Workers follow afterwards with `kubeadm upgrade node`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/kubeadm/kubeadm-upgrade/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Upgrading kubeadm clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$On a kubeadm cluster, what is the recommended order to upgrade the control plane minor version?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You back up etcd with `ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot save /backup/snap.db`. To restore on a new control plane you should:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Copy snap.db into /var/lib/etcd and restart etcd."},{"id":"b","text":"Run `etcdctl snapshot restore /backup/snap.db --data-dir=/var/lib/etcd-from-backup` then point the etcd static pod at the new data-dir."},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl apply -f snap.db"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl restart etcd — it auto-detects snapshots"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Restore writes a brand-new data directory; you then update the etcd static Pod's `--data-dir` (and hostPath volume) to that directory. Simply copying the snapshot file is not a valid restore.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/configure-upgrade-etcd/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Operating etcd"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You back up etcd with `ETCDCTL_API=3 etcdctl snapshot save /backup/snap.db`. To restore on a new control plane you should:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which Role permits read-only access to ConfigMaps in one namespace?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"apiGroups: [\"\"], resources: [\"configmaps\"], verbs: [\"get\",\"list\",\"watch\"]"},{"id":"b","text":"apiGroups: [\"*\"], resources: [\"*\"], verbs: [\"*\"]"},{"id":"c","text":"apiGroups: [\"rbac.authorization.k8s.io\"], resources: [\"configmaps\"], verbs: [\"read\"]"},{"id":"d","text":"apiGroups: [\"core/v1\"], resources: [\"configmap\"], verbs: [\"view\"]"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$ConfigMaps are in the core API group (the empty string). Read-only verbs are `get`, `list`, `watch`. Roles vs ClusterRoles differ in scope; this would be a Role for one namespace.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/rbac/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — RBAC"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which Role permits read-only access to ConfigMaps in one namespace?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command installs Calico via its tigera-operator manifest?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl create -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/projectcalico/calico/v3.29.2/manifests/tigera-operator.yaml"},{"id":"b","text":"kubeadm init --pod-network-cni=calico"},{"id":"c","text":"helm install calico stable/calico"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl plugin install calico"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Modern Calico installs in two steps: apply `tigera-operator.yaml`, then `custom-resources.yaml` for the operator to roll out the dataplane. There is no `kubectl plugin install calico` command.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/extend-kubernetes/compute-storage-net/network-plugins/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Network Plugins (CNI)"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command installs Calico via its tigera-operator manifest?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Across a cluster the kubelet must be configured to set `--cluster-dns=10.96.0.10`. On a kubeadm cluster the canonical place to change this is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Edit /var/lib/kubelet/config.yaml on each node manually."},{"id":"b","text":"Edit the `kubelet-config` ConfigMap in kube-system; nodes pick it up after a kubelet restart (or `kubeadm upgrade node`)."},{"id":"c","text":"Edit /etc/systemd/system/kubelet.service.d/10-kubeadm.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"Run `kubectl set cluster-dns 10.96.0.10`"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$kubeadm centralizes kubelet config in the `kubelet-config` ConfigMap; `kubeadm upgrade node` regenerates the on-node config from it. Hand-editing per-node config drifts and is overwritten on the next upgrade.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Across a cluster the kubelet must be configured to set `--cluster-dns=10.96.0.10`. On a kubeadm cluster the canonical place to change this is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A wordpress Deployment in namespace `relative-fawn` must request 247m CPU and 5417Mi memory per container. The cleanest way to add resource requests to a running Deployment is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl scale deploy wordpress --replicas=0; edit the Deployment to add `resources.requests`; scale back up."},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl patch pod ..."},{"id":"c","text":"Delete the namespace and re-apply."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a LimitRange — Deployment spec does not support resources."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Editing `spec.template.spec.containers[].resources.requests` on the Deployment is the right pattern; scaling to 0 first avoids partial rollout churn. Patching individual Pods is ignored — they belong to a ReplicaSet.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Resource Management"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A wordpress Deployment in namespace `relative-fawn` must request 247m CPU and 5417Mi memory per container. The cleanest way to add resource requests to a running Deployment is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$An HPA targets a Deployment with `minReplicas: 1, maxReplicas: 4, averageUtilization: 50% CPU` and `behavior.scaleDown.stabilizationWindowSeconds: 30`. What does the stabilization window do?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Waits 30s of sustained low load before each scale-down to dampen flapping."},{"id":"b","text":"Caps scale-down to 30s total."},{"id":"c","text":"Disables scaling for the first 30s."},{"id":"d","text":"Waits 30s between Pod terminations."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$The stabilization window is the look-back used to pick the highest recommended replicas — for scale-down a longer window dampens reactions to brief utilization dips.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/run-application/horizontal-pod-autoscale/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Horizontal Pod Autoscaling"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$An HPA targets a Deployment with `minReplicas: 1, maxReplicas: 4, averageUtilization: 50% CPU` and `behavior.scaleDown.stabilizationWindowSeconds: 30`. What does the stabilization window do?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Workloads and Scheduling$k8s$, 3, $k8s$MULTI$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Select ALL true statements about DaemonSets.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"A DaemonSet ensures one (or some) Pod runs on every matching node."},{"id":"b","text":"DaemonSet Pods bypass the default scheduler; the kubelet binds them directly."},{"id":"c","text":"Adding a node automatically creates a Pod from the DaemonSet on that node."},{"id":"d","text":"A DaemonSet works well for node-level agents (CNI, log collectors, monitoring)."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a","c","d"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Since k8s 1.17 the default scheduler IS used for DaemonSet Pods (controller adds NodeAffinity); they are no longer scheduled directly by the kubelet. The other three are textbook DaemonSet properties.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/controllers/daemonset/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — DaemonSet"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Select ALL true statements about DaemonSets.$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Service `db` in namespace `production` is addressed by Pods in namespace `web` as:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"db"},{"id":"b","text":"db.web.svc.cluster.local"},{"id":"c","text":"db.production.svc.cluster.local"},{"id":"d","text":"production.db.cluster.local"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["c"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Cross-namespace DNS uses `<svc>.<ns>.svc.cluster.local`. Same-namespace short names (`db`) resolve via the DNS search list.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/dns-pod-service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — DNS for Services and Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Service `db` in namespace `production` is addressed by Pods in namespace `web` as:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You replace an Ingress with a Gateway+HTTPRoute. The HTTPRoute must select an existing Gateway. Which field links them?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"spec.gatewayName"},{"id":"b","text":"spec.parentRefs"},{"id":"c","text":"metadata.ownerReferences"},{"id":"d","text":"spec.controller"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$HTTPRoute uses `spec.parentRefs` (a list of objects) to attach to one or more Gateways/listeners. There is no `gatewayName` field on HTTPRoute.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://gateway-api.sigs.k8s.io/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Gateway API"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You replace an Ingress with a Gateway+HTTPRoute. The HTTPRoute must select an existing Gateway. Which field links them?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A LoadBalancer Service stays `Pending`. The cluster is bare-metal. The MOST appropriate fix is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Wait — kube-controller-manager will create the load balancer eventually."},{"id":"b","text":"Install a bare-metal LB provider such as MetalLB or kube-vip."},{"id":"c","text":"Switch the Service to ExternalName."},{"id":"d","text":"Set `externalTrafficPolicy: Local`."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Cloud LoadBalancers are reconciled by a cloud-controller. On bare metal you need MetalLB / kube-vip / similar to allocate external IPs. `externalTrafficPolicy` only affects packet routing, not allocation.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Services"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A LoadBalancer Service stays `Pending`. The cluster is bare-metal. The MOST appropriate fix is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Services and Networking$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$CoreDNS pods are CrashLoopBackOff with "Loop (127.0.0.1:53 -> :53) detected for zone .". The fix is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Delete CoreDNS Pods — the issue is transient."},{"id":"b","text":"In the CoreDNS Corefile, replace the upstream `forward . /etc/resolv.conf` with explicit upstream resolvers (e.g. 8.8.8.8) so it does not forward to itself."},{"id":"c","text":"Disable kube-proxy."},{"id":"d","text":"Set Pod DNS policy to `None`."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A loop occurs when the node's /etc/resolv.conf points to a local resolver that itself forwards to CoreDNS. Replace the forward target with the actual upstream DNS or fix the host resolv.conf.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/dns-pod-service/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — DNS for Services and Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$CoreDNS pods are CrashLoopBackOff with "Loop (127.0.0.1:53 -> :53) detected for zone .". The fix is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Create a new StorageClass `low-latency` using the local-path provisioner that defers binding until a Pod needs the volume. Which `volumeBindingMode` is correct?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Immediate"},{"id":"b","text":"WaitForFirstConsumer"},{"id":"c","text":"OnDemand"},{"id":"d","text":"Deferred"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`WaitForFirstConsumer` postpones PV provisioning and binding until a Pod using the PVC is scheduled — essential for topology-aware (e.g. local) volumes. `OnDemand`/`Deferred` are not valid values.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/storage-classes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Storage Classes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Create a new StorageClass `low-latency` using the local-path provisioner that defers binding until a Pod needs the volume. Which `volumeBindingMode` is correct?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Storage$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A PVC requests 250Mi but the matching pre-provisioned PV is 1Gi. The binding behavior is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Fails — sizes must match exactly."},{"id":"b","text":"Succeeds — the PVC binds to a PV whose capacity is ≥ requested."},{"id":"c","text":"Succeeds — but the Pod sees only 250Mi."},{"id":"d","text":"Fails — capacity downscaling is not allowed."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PV binding requires capacity ≥ requested. The Pod sees the full PV capacity; the PVC field is a *minimum* request, not a quota.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/storage/persistent-volumes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Persistent Volumes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A PVC requests 250Mi but the matching pre-provisioned PV is 1Gi. The binding behavior is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command lists running containers on a node using the CRI directly (independent of kubectl)?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"docker ps"},{"id":"b","text":"crictl ps"},{"id":"c","text":"kubeadm ps"},{"id":"d","text":"systemctl list-containers"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`crictl` is the standard CLI for CRI-compatible runtimes (containerd, cri-o, cri-dockerd) and is what the CKA exam expects on modern clusters. `docker ps` only works if a Docker runtime is installed.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/container-runtimes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Container Runtimes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command lists running containers on a node using the CRI directly (independent of kubectl)?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A Pod has `ImagePullBackOff` and `kubectl describe pod` shows "pull access denied for private/repo:v1". The fix is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a `kubernetes.io/dockerconfigjson` Secret and reference it via `spec.imagePullSecrets`."},{"id":"b","text":"Restart the kubelet."},{"id":"c","text":"Set `imagePullPolicy: Never`."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a NodePort Service for the registry."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Authenticated pulls require an `imagePullSecrets` reference on the Pod (or ServiceAccount) containing a `dockerconfigjson` Secret with the registry credentials.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubectl Reference"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A Pod has `ImagePullBackOff` and `kubectl describe pod` shows "pull access denied for private/repo:v1". The fix is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Two containers in a Pod must communicate over a NEW TLS-1.3-only nginx config exposed via a ConfigMap. After editing the ConfigMap, the new TLS settings are not active. The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"ConfigMaps mounted as a volume update lazily — restart the Deployment so the new file is read at startup, or use a sidecar that watches for changes."},{"id":"b","text":"TLS 1.3 is not supported in Kubernetes."},{"id":"c","text":"The kube-proxy must be restarted."},{"id":"d","text":"NetworkPolicy is dropping the connection."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$ConfigMap volume mounts are eventually consistent, but the consuming process (nginx) only re-reads on reload. `kubectl rollout restart deploy` or sending a SIGHUP via a sidecar applies the new config.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/kubectl/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubectl Reference"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Two containers in a Pod must communicate over a NEW TLS-1.3-only nginx config exposed via a ConfigMap. After editing the ConfigMap, the new TLS settings are not active. The MOST likely cause is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Inspecting `journalctl -u kubelet -f` reveals "Failed to start ContainerManager: failed to initialise top-level QOS containers: ... cgroupfs vs systemd". The fix is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"Set the kubelet `cgroupDriver` to match the container runtime (typically `systemd` on modern installs)."},{"id":"b","text":"Disable swap."},{"id":"c","text":"Reinstall the OS."},{"id":"d","text":"Upgrade kubectl."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$kubelet and CRI must agree on the cgroup driver. On systemd-based hosts both should use `systemd`. Mismatched drivers prevent the kubelet from starting.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/container-runtimes/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Container Runtimes"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Inspecting `journalctl -u kubelet -f` reveals "Failed to start ContainerManager: failed to initialise top-level QOS containers: ... cgroupfs vs systemd". The fix is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$`kubectl get nodes` returns "Unable to connect to the server: x509: certificate signed by unknown authority". The MOST likely root cause for a working operator is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The cluster is down."},{"id":"b","text":"Your kubeconfig points to a stale CA — refresh the kubeconfig (e.g. `kubeadm kubeconfig user --client-name=admin` or pull a fresh one)."},{"id":"c","text":"CoreDNS is broken."},{"id":"d","text":"kube-proxy is in iptables mode."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$TLS verification failure against the API server's cert almost always means the kubeconfig CA does not match — rotate or regenerate the kubeconfig.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/debug-cluster/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Troubleshooting Clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$`kubectl get nodes` returns "Unable to connect to the server: x509: certificate signed by unknown authority". The MOST likely root cause for a working operator is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Troubleshooting$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$A control-plane Pod (e.g. kube-scheduler) is missing from `kubectl get pods -n kube-system`. The kubelet logs show it is "not running". The first place to look is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"/var/log/syslog"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/kubernetes/manifests/kube-scheduler.yaml — confirm the static-Pod file exists and is syntactically valid."},{"id":"c","text":"systemctl status kube-scheduler"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl describe deploy kube-scheduler -n kube-system"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["b"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$On kubeadm clusters scheduler/controller-manager/apiserver run as static Pods from `/etc/kubernetes/manifests/`. A missing or broken manifest is the typical cause. There is no Deployment or systemd unit for them.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/control-plane-flags/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kube-apiserver Static Pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$A control-plane Pod (e.g. kube-scheduler) is missing from `kubectl get pods -n kube-system`. The kubelet logs show it is "not running". The first place to look is:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which kernel module and sysctl are required for kube-proxy/CNI iptables traffic to work on a kubeadm node?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"br_netfilter module + net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables=1"},{"id":"b","text":"overlay module only"},{"id":"c","text":"ip_vs module + net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies=0"},{"id":"d","text":"nf_conntrack module + vm.max_map_count=262144"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Loading `br_netfilter` and setting `net.bridge.bridge-nf-call-iptables=1` (plus `net.ipv4.ip_forward=1`) lets bridged traffic traverse iptables so Service/Pod networking functions.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which kernel module and sysctl are required for kube-proxy/CNI iptables traffic to work on a kubeadm node?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$To create a ClusterRole that allows reading Pods and a ClusterRoleBinding to group `developers` imperatively, you run:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl create clusterrole pod-reader --verb=get,list,watch --resource=pods && kubectl create clusterrolebinding dev-read --clusterrole=pod-reader --group=developers"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl create role pod-reader --verb=* --resource=pods"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl create rolebinding dev-read --role=pod-reader --user=developers"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl auth grant developers pods"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A cluster-wide read needs a ClusterRole bound by a ClusterRoleBinding; binding to a `--group` grants every member. A Role/RoleBinding would only scope to one namespace.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/rbac/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — RBAC"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$To create a ClusterRole that allows reading Pods and a ClusterRoleBinding to group `developers` imperatively, you run:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which command verifies whether ServiceAccount `build:ci` may create deployments in namespace `build`?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubectl auth can-i create deployments --as=system:serviceaccount:build:ci -n build"},{"id":"b","text":"kubectl get rolebinding ci -n build"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl describe sa ci -n build"},{"id":"d","text":"kubectl auth whoami --sa ci"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubectl auth can-i ... --as=system:serviceaccount:<ns>:<name>` impersonates the SA and reports whether RBAC permits the action — the canonical RBAC verification command.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/reference/access-authn-authz/rbac/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — RBAC"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which command verifies whether ServiceAccount `build:ci` may create deployments in namespace `build`?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$During `kubeadm upgrade`, before draining a control-plane node you should verify the plan with:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubeadm upgrade plan"},{"id":"b","text":"kubeadm config images list"},{"id":"c","text":"kubeadm token list"},{"id":"d","text":"kubeadm certs check-expiration"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubeadm upgrade plan` shows the current versions, the available target versions, and component upgrade actions — always run before `kubeadm upgrade apply`.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/kubeadm/kubeadm-upgrade/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Upgrading kubeadm clusters"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$During `kubeadm upgrade`, before draining a control-plane node you should verify the plan with:$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$After restoring etcd to `/var/lib/etcd-restore`, what must be updated in the etcd static Pod manifest?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"The `--data-dir` flag and the corresponding hostPath volume must point to /var/lib/etcd-restore."},{"id":"b","text":"Only the container image tag."},{"id":"c","text":"The `--listen-peer-urls` to 2379."},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — etcd auto-discovers the restored data."}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$A restore creates a new data directory; the etcd static Pod must reference it via `--data-dir` and its hostPath volume so the kubelet starts etcd from the restored data.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/administer-cluster/configure-upgrade-etcd/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — Operating etcd"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$After restoring etcd to `/var/lib/etcd-restore`, what must be updated in the etcd static Pod manifest?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 2, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$Which file does `kubeadm init` write that you copy to `$HOME/.kube/config` for cluster-admin access?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"/etc/kubernetes/admin.conf"},{"id":"b","text":"/etc/kubernetes/kubelet.conf"},{"id":"c","text":"/etc/kubernetes/scheduler.conf"},{"id":"d","text":"/var/lib/kubelet/config.yaml"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`/etc/kubernetes/admin.conf` is the cluster-admin kubeconfig generated by kubeadm. `kubelet.conf`/`scheduler.conf` are component kubeconfigs with scoped identities.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, true, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$Which file does `kubeadm init` write that you copy to `$HOME/.kube/config` for cluster-admin access?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 4, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$You add a second control-plane node. The join command must include which extra flag beyond a worker join?$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"--control-plane (with an uploaded certificate key)"},{"id":"b","text":"--node-role=master"},{"id":"c","text":"--etcd-only"},{"id":"d","text":"--skip-phases=addon"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$Joining a control-plane node uses `kubeadm join --control-plane` plus `--certificate-key` (from `kubeadm init phase upload-certs` / `--upload-certs`) so the new node receives the control-plane PKI.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$You add a second control-plane node. The join command must include which extra flag beyond a worker join?$k8s$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", domain, difficulty, type, stem, options, correct, explanation, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", version, "createdAt", "updatedAt") SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $k8s$Cluster Architecture, Installation and Configuration$k8s$, 3, $k8s$SINGLE$k8s$::"QType", $k8s$kubeadm-managed certificates are expiring. The command to renew all of them is:$k8s$, $k8s$[{"id":"a","text":"kubeadm certs renew all"},{"id":"b","text":"kubeadm init --renew-certs"},{"id":"c","text":"kubectl certificate approve --all"},{"id":"d","text":"openssl req -renew -in admin.conf"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$["a"]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$`kubeadm certs renew all` renews every kubeadm-managed control-plane certificate. The control-plane static Pods then need a restart to pick up the new certs.$k8s$, $k8s$[{"url":"https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/production-environment/tools/kubeadm/","label":"Kubernetes Docs — kubeadm"}]$k8s$::jsonb, $k8s$PUBLISHED$k8s$::"QStatus", $k8s$manual:cka-seed$k8s$, false, 1, NOW(), NOW() FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = $k8s$CKA-P2$k8s$ AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $k8s$kubeadm-managed certificates are expiring. The command to renew all of them is:$k8s$);
